The bombings there of churches and other sites were allegedly staged by two obscure Islamist groups, National Thowheed Jamaath and Jammiyathul Millathu Ibrahim — with the Islamic State claiming that it also played a role.
She explains that the Islamic State’s global network has grown so rapidly over the past five years that it’s bigger now than al-Qaeda ever was.
The United States took down the leadership of al-Qaeda, to be sure, just as it did later against the Islamic State.
The United States can’t do this job by itself, even if it tries.
We’ve certainly found that out, but the United States remains the essential partner.